{{- heading("A Basic Introduction to the World Assembly") -}}
{{- section("How can I draft a proposal?") -}}
Drafting proposals is a relatively straightforward process. The largest contributor to complexity is interacting with feedback and time spent working. But first, let's examine the initial steps.

To start, you will want to have a solid topic to write about. This can be almost anything; however, the best topics are ones that can be applied internationally. When considering topics, make sure to weigh whether it is really an international issue, and how members could be affected. Once you have one, start writing! Your first draft(s) may not be very pretty, but the intent is to find how your idea works best. Play around with a draft until you are satisfied, and once you are, post a new thread in the General Assembly forum on NS. This step allows others to see and review your proposal easily for the next step.

Once you have put out a public draft, other players will be able to comment as they please. When receiving feedback, be courteous of others and recognize that they are trying to be helpful. Weigh the feedback and determine whether it is worth implementing into the proposal. Drafting can be short or it can be long; while a month of drafting time is recommended as a minimum, longer development can be very helpful to making sure your proposal is refined, especially if it is on a more complex topic.

When you are fully satisfied with your draft, you can submit your proposal and get approvals. Don't be afraid to pull it back if a critical issue is found; a strong proposal is much more likely to pass.
{{- endsection() -}}
