{{- endsection() -}}
{{- section("What are all these repeals? What does 'NatSov' mean?") -}}
The modern General Assembly (GA) is broadly divided into two camps - National Sovereigntists (NatSovs) and International Federalists (IntFeds). Broadly speaking, NatSovs support the freedom of individual nations to decide their own laws and policies (i.e. have sovereignty), whereas IntFeds prefer using the World Assembly to mandate improvements to all member states. Currently, NatSovs are firmly in control of the General Assembly, not least because of the major voting bloc, the Sovereign Seven (S7), which adopts a National Sovereignty position, and of which Starlight & Horizon is a member. At the time of writing, the S7 maintains over 1650 combined Delegate endorsements, providing it with a powerful base to control the GA. This NatSov stance is also responsible for the large number of repeals seen in the GA as of late, as proposals against NatSov ideas are struck out from the books (as well as those which are more generally outdated). 

The GA is also currently being reformed by the NS staff team as part of their GA 2026 plan, of which the most key aspect is the 'reset' - where, on July 1st 2026, all existing GA resolutions will be permanently archived, leaving a blank canvas for authors to start work. This has led to the proliferation of so-called 'post-reset' drafts: proposals planned to be submitted immediately after the reset occurs, and likely leading to a months-long queue forming. No prominent authors are submitting drafts to the current GA queue - all proposals in the queue at the time of the reset will be discarded, and as there are enough proposals currently to last until past the reset, there is no need to submit more. 
{{- endsection() -}}
